    {
      "block_id": "1ce4750c-f3ba-8019-8c61-fd835c894b80",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Flaw of Previous Models",
          "Novelty of Model",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "Correct on First Attempt",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "97 students at an US university, 912 ASSISTments learners, 66 Andes learners, 120 KDDCup learners, 1024 Mc-Graw Hill learners, 478 Mechanical Turk learners, ",
          "1 Chinese Language course, ASSISTments, Cognitivite, Andes, Mc-Graw Hill",
          "LMS logs, Answer Sequences",
          "[lineafm, logafm, powafm, recency, expdecafm, base, base2, ppe, logsuc, linesuc, logfail, linefail, expdecsuc, expdecfail, basesuc, basefail, base2fail, base2suc, linecomp, prop, propdec, logit, logitdec]",
          "Most currently available models such as BKT, DKT, Additive Factor Models, Performance Factors Analysis are relatively strict in terms of the data they are allowed to take in order to obtain meaningful predictions. ",
          "LKT allows the encompassing of different forms of features, making it a flexible framework for knowledge modelling even if it may not be the best performing approach to student modelling.",
          "Authors filtered out all attempts that are beyond the first attempt at an exercise. \n\nExercises were divided into 5 knowledge components and each feature was created from the corresponding data sources.\n\nModelling becomes the implementation of a logistic regression suing specific subsets of features.",
          "AFM_1, AFM_2, PFA_1, PFA_2, PFA_3, PFA_Decay, R_PFA_1, R_PFA_2, R_PFA_3, PPE, LKT_1, LKT_2",
          "100-Repeated Holdout",
          "Mechanical Turk\n{R-Squared: 0.346 - propeckc+ppekc, RMSE: 0.39 - propeckc+ppekc, AUC: 0.857 - propeckc+ppekc}\n\nChinese\n{R-Squared: 0.113 - logsuckc+logfailkc+recencykc & expdecsuckc + expdecfailkc, RMSE: 0.381 - logsuckc+logfailkc+recencykn & expdecsuckc + expdecfailkc, & logsuckc+logfailkc & propdeckc+expdecfailkc, AUC: 0.725 - propdeckc+expdecfailkc & expdecsuckc + expdecfailkc}\n\n\nASSISTments\n{R-Squared: 0.126 - propeckc+ppekc, RMSE: 0.451 - propeckc+ppekc, AUC: 0.726 - propeckc+ppekc & logsuckc+logfailkc+recencykc}\n\nKDDCup\n{R-Squared: 0.169 - propeckc+ppekc, RMSE: 0.37 - propeckc+ppekc, AUC: 0.768 - propeckc+ppekc}\n\nAndes\n{R-Squared: 0.165 - propeckc+ppekc, RMSE: 0.386 - propeckc+ppekc, AUC: 0.762 - propeckc+ppekc}\n\nMcGraw Hill\n{R-Squared: 0.275 - propeckc+ppekc, RMSE: 0.388 - propeckc+ppekc, AUC: 0.823 - propeckc+ppekc}",
          "Authors argue for LKT as a useful framework of KT that can be used as an alternative to BKT and/or DKT. \n\nThey make a comparison of 12 alternative models that mix Additive Factor Analysis, Performance Factor Analysis and their own LKT proposals. \n\n;odels predict probability of getting answer correct on first attempt which obviously is later converted into a probability.\n\nModel propeckc+ppekc seems to almost consistently outperform the remaining options.",
          "No comparison against KT models who have been more successful such as BKT and/or DKT.\n\nMost models seem to substantially underfit (as highlighted by across the board low values of RSquared).\n\nHiearchy of features needs to be pre-deternmined before being given into the models. \n\nLimited support for random effects.\n\n\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
